<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Words Starting With RE-</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">Quiz · Bingo</p>

    <!-- Additional depth content -->
    <div class="mt-10 border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 pt-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">Why RE- Dominates Every Game</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">RE- is the single most versatile prefix in Scrabble. With over 1000 valid words, you almost always have an RE- play available regardless of your rack or the board state. This makes it the first prefix every serious player should master.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">The two-letter base cost (R1+E1 = 2 points) means RE- doesn't waste your scoring potential. All your power comes from the root word. Combine RE- with J, X, Z, or Q roots for devastating plays: REJUDGE, REFIX, REZONE, REQUIZ.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">RE is also one of the most useful 2-letter words in the game. Use it for parallel plays — placing RE alongside existing words to score in two directions simultaneously. This technique alone can add 10-15 points per turn.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">For bingo hunters, RE- is the easiest prefix to hit naturally. R and E are among the most common draws in the bag (6 R tiles, 12 E tiles). When you spot them together on your rack, immediately start looking for 5-letter roots to complete a bingo.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">Study these high-frequency RE- roots for instant recall: BUILD, MAKE, PLAY, WRITE, TURN, MOVE, PLACE, CHECK, ZONE, FIX, WAX. Each creates a valid and recognisable extension that rarely gets challenged.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">REX (10 points) deserves special mention as one of the highest-scoring 3-letter words in the game. The X tile's 8-point value plus R and E gives you a compact power play for tight board situations.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">In tournament play, RE- words dominate opening strategy. Many top players use RE- extensions in their first three moves to establish board control while keeping their rack flexible for future draws.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Advanced tip: track how many R tiles remain in the bag (6 total) and E tiles (12 total). With these common letters, RE- stays viable throughout the entire game — unlike rarer prefixes that depend on specific tile draws.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">For rack management, holding R+E early is rarely a bad decision. These tiles combine with almost anything, and the RE- option provides a safety net if your remaining tiles don't form strong independent words.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Finally, remember that RE- words hook easily. REZONE can take S (REZONES), REFIX can take ED (REFIXED). These extensions give you scoring opportunities on future turns from the same play.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Bottom line: RE- is the most powerful prefix in Scrabble by sheer volume and flexibility. With 1000+ words and a dirt-cheap 2-point cost, it should be the first prefix you master on your competitive journey.</p>
    </div>

    
<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Advanced Rack Management</h2>

<p>Elite Scrabble players think in terms of rack leave — the tiles remaining after each play. A good rack leave balances vowels and consonants (ideally 3-4 consonants and 2-3 vowels), retains common letters like S, E, R, T, and avoids duplicates. Every word you play should be evaluated not just by its score but by what it leaves you to work with next turn.</p>

<p>The concept of synergy applies to Scrabble tiles just as it does to other games. Certain tile combinations work together beautifully — for example, holding ING or TION or NESS makes it easier to find 7-letter bingos. Conversely, holding double or triple copies of the same letter severely limits your options and often forces an exchange.</p>

<p>Tile tracking becomes increasingly important as the game progresses. By the midgame, you should have a rough idea of which high-value tiles remain in the bag. In the endgame (fewer than 7 tiles left in the bag), precise tracking allows you to deduce your opponent's exact rack and play accordingly — blocking their best plays while maximising your own remaining scoring opportunities.</p>

<p>Consider the concept of turnover — how many tiles you draw from the bag each turn. Playing 5-6 tiles per turn cycles through the bag faster, giving you more chances to draw premium tiles. Conversely, playing single-tile or two-tile words slows your turnover and reduces your overall access to the tile distribution across the full game.</p>

